success.question_text: If the pattern continues, what will be the 43rd letter?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Patterns

stimulus_1.text: The letters A, B, C and D are used to make a repeating pattern.

review_3.column_1_text:
The letters C, D, A, B are repeating. So four letters are repeating. Every fourth letter will be B.

So the 44th letter will be B.

The 43rd letter will be the letter before B in the pattern.

A is the 43rd letter.

Tip

A pattern can be formed from symbols and objects as well as numbers. Once the pattern is discovered decisions can be made about the way it continues.

success.question_text: In how many different combinations could you choose three colours from seven?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Patterns

stimulus_1.text: This pattern is known as Pascal’s triangle.

stimulus_3.text: The numbers in the rows of Pascal’s triangle can be used to find the number of possible combinations of different colours when choosing from a certain number of colours. For example, supposing you are choosing from four different colours: red, blue, green and yellow. Using Row 4 of Pascal’s triangle, you can see that there is 1 choice for having none of the four colours. There are 4 choices for just one colour (red, blue, green or yellow) and 6 choices for combinations of any two of the colours (red/blue, red/green, red/yellow, blue/green, blue/yellow and green/yellow). There are 4 choices for combinations of three colours (red/blue/green, red/blue/yellow, red/green/yellow and blue/green/yellow) and 1 choice for all four colours.

stimulus_4.text: If you were choosing from five colours you would use Row 5. There is 1 choice for none of the colours, 5 choices for just one colour, 10 choices for combinations of two colours and so on.

review_3.column_1_text:
Row 7 is 1   7   21   35   35   21   7   1.

There is 1 choice for none of the colours, 7 choices for one colour, 21 choices for combinations of two colours and 35 choices for combinations of three colours.

The number of different combinations is 35.

Tip

Read all the given information carefully. Read it again and again if necessary.

The numbers are starting at 6 and counting forward by 8.

The extended sequence is 6, 14, 22, 30, 38, 46, 54, 62, …

This means the eighth number is 62.
